<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n34001b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n34" href="#n34001b">N34 (VI.B.27)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n34all.htm#n34001b"> 1(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Theotokos</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">The council of Ephesus (<year>A.D.</year> 431), the third oecumenical, had insisted upon applying the term <mark>Theotokos</mark> to the Virgin Mary, and this was repeated in the symbol of Chalcedon, which says that Christ was born of the Virgin Mary, the Theotokos, &ldquo;according to the manhood&rdquo;. The same symbol also declares that Christ is &ldquo;to be acknowledged in two natures &hellip; indivisibly and inseparably&rdquo;. <small> &ldquo;ORTHODOX EASTERN CHURCH&rdquo; <a name="EBOEC" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#EBOEC"><cite title="source">Encyclopaedia Britannica</cite></a>, 11th edit. (1911) 334 [Controversies and Schisms]</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
